events.description: A partial US government shutdown that delayed key economic data releases.
President Trump signed a budget to end the partial government shutdown.

events.event_name: Nomination of Kevin Warsh as Fed chair
events.description: Donald Trump nominated Kevin Warsh to succeed as the next Federal Reserve chair.
Recent release of strong manufacturing data in the US.

facts.fact_text: The dollar index was positioned at approximately 97.4 on Wednesday.

evidences.evidence_text: The dollar index held around 97.4 on Wednesday

facts.fact_text: A $1.2 trillion budget was signed by President Trump to conclude the partial shutdown.

evidences.evidence_text: President Donald Trump signed a $1.2 trillion budget to end the partial shutdown

facts.fact_text: The January jobs report and job openings data were delayed.

evidences.evidence_text: The latest job openings data and the January jobs report, both scheduled for this week, were postponed

claims.claim_text: Kevin Warsh is perceived as a less dovish candidate for the Fed chair position.

evidences.evidence_text: Trump nominated Kevin Warsh as the next Federal Reserve chair, a pick seen as less dovish than other candidates

claims.claim_text: The Federal Reserve is expected by markets to cut interest rates twice in the current year.
claims.author: Markets

evidences.evidence_text: Markets still anticipate the Fed could lower rates twice this year, possibly in June and October.

claims.claim_text: Strong manufacturing performance has reduced the likelihood of aggressive interest rate reductions.

evidences.evidence_text: strong US manufacturing data tempered expectations for rapid rate cuts.

evidence.evidence_text: the partial government shutdown delayed key economic releases
the dollar had gained in recent sessions after Trump nominated Kevin Warsh
strong US manufacturing data tempered expectations for rapid rate cuts.
